Class ValidCommand

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.dnddev.factions.api.commands.ValidCommand
  • Direct Known Subclasses:

    public abstract class ValidCommand
extends Object
    Represents a command that can be used by Users on the server.

      • ValidCommand

        public ValidCommand(String name,
                    String description,
                    Permission permission,
                    boolean blocksConsole,
                    String[] aliases)
        Constructs a new command with the given arguments. This will initialize the arguments list as well as the values table. Additionally, it will automatically convert all aliases to lowercase.
        Parameters:
        name - the name of the command.
        description - the description of the command.
        permission - the required permission for the command.
        blocksConsole - if this command is unusable by the console.
        aliases - the aliases of the command.

    • Method Detail

      • process

        protected void process(CommandSender sender,
                       String[] label,
                       String[] rawArguments)
        This method runs the command. It goes through each argument and will process and validate it. Then, so long as that passes, it will run the command's system. Last it will clear out any saved table data and stored argument values.
        Parameters:
        sender - the sender of the command.
        label - the label from which the command was sent
        rawArguments - the unparsed and non-validated arguments.

      • processTabComplete

        public List<String> processTabComplete(CommandSender sender,
                                       String[] rawArguments)
        Process the tab complete for the given command. This also takes into account the fact the last argument provided is what is supposed to be changed. The arguments passed include only the arguments for the command, and not the actual label used. The raw arguments passed should always have at least a length of 1.
        Parameters:
        sender - the person who sent the tab request.
        rawArguments - the arguments already typed by the player.
        Returns:
        the suggestions for tab complete.

      • validRun

        public abstract void validRun(CommandSender sender,
                              String[] label,
                              List<CommandArgument<?>> arguments)
        Runs the command after all processing has already been completed. The label is an array of the label used by this command as well as any parent command. The arguments will always be there, whether they are used or not. To check if optional arguments were used, call the method CommandArgument.hasValue().
        Parameters:
        sender - the sender of the command.
        label - the label of the command.
        arguments - the arguments of the command.

      • getValues

        public Table<Integer,Class<?>,Object> getValues()
        The table of the already processed values. -1 corresponds to the sender. Every other number corresponds to the ordinal of the argument. In the process of running the command, it will always grab the sender's session.
        Returns:
        the already processed values.

      • getArgumentNames

        public String[] getArgumentNames()
        Returns:
        an array of all the names of the arguments.

      • getMinimumLength

        protected int getMinimumLength()
        The lowest possible length that the number of raw arguments is capable of being. This is the count of the number of arguments that are not optional.
        Returns:
        the minimum length of the raw command arguments.

      • getMaximumLength

        protected int getMaximumLength()
        The highest possible length that the number of raw arguments is capable of being. For non-variable-length commands, this is the size of all the arguments. For variable-length commands, it is Integer.MAX_VALUE.
        Returns:
        the maximum length of the raw command arguments.

      • addArgument

        protected void addArgument(CommandArgument<?> argument)
        Adds a new argument to be used by the command. Will throw an IllegalArgumentException in one of two cases. First, if the given argument is required and the previous argument is not optional. Second, if the argument before it is of variable length. Both of these cases are not supported as there is no perfect way to ensure that the arguments will always capture the desired input.
        Parameters:
        argument - the new argument

        Parameters:

        Returns:
        whether or not the argument still existed.

      • getArguments

        public List<CommandArgument<?>> getArguments()
        Return an unmodifiable view of the arguments for this command. To add a new argument use addArgument(CommandArgument). To remove an existing argument use removeArgument(CommandArgument).
        Returns:
        the current existing arguments.

      • getDescription

        public String getDescription()
        Returns the description of the command. This is given to Bukkit when the command is properly registered within their system. There is no method to change this, and if it is changed via reflection, that change will not be reflected within Bukkit's command system.
        Returns:
        the description of the command.

      • getName

        public String getName()
        Returns the name of the command. This is what is used to register the command within Bukkit, as well as the primary way to reference the command elsewhere. There is no method to change this, and if it is changed via reflection, that change will not be reflected within Bukkit's command system.
        Returns:
        the name of the command.
